  "prompt": "How do I draw realistic hair with pencil?",
  "response": "Drawing realistic hair with a pencil requires practice and attention to detail. Here are some tips:\n\n1. Observe hair carefully\n- Study hair's texture, flow, and how light reflects off it\n- Notice how individual strands group together\n\n2. Basic techniques\n- Use light, loose strokes following hair's natural direction\n- Vary pencil pressure to create depth and dimension\n- Layer strokes gradually, building up tone and texture\n\n3. Tools and materials\n- Use a range of pencil hardnesses (B, 2B, 4B)\n- Have a good eraser for highlights\n- Use blending stumps for smooth transitions\n\n4. Specific drawing steps\n- Sketch hair's overall shape and flow first\n- Draw larger sections before individual strands\n- Start with lighter lines, then add darker details\n- Create volume by varying stroke density\n- Add highlights with eraser\n\n5. Tips for different hair types\n- Straight hair: Smooth, linear strokes\n- Curly hair: More irregular, clustered strokes\n- Wavy hair: Flowing, curved lines\n\n6. Practice techniques\n- Draw from reference photos\n- Practice different hair textures\n- Study light and shadow\n- Experiment with different pencil techniques\n\nRemember, patience and consistent practice are key to improving hair drawing skills.",
